90% reduction of a predefined stimulus. Unit of Measure is always % when normalized to the dynamic range of the assay.

Measured / detected concentration of the perturbagen / compound in the assay or a subsystem (locally) in the assay. For example measured absolute concentration in the brain. This is in contrast to screening concentration, which is the (final assumed) concentration of a compound added to the assay.

Clearance is the volume of plasma from which the drug is completely removed per unit time, or, alternatively, the volume of plasma that would have to lose all of the drug that it contains within a unit of time to account for an observed rate of drug elimination.
The time taken for the concentration of the drug in a particular tissue or blood plasma to decrease by half.
The time taken for the concentration of the drug in an in-vitro system (e.g., liver microsomes) to decrease by half.
The area under the drug concentration-time curve following an oral dose.
The area under the drug concentration-time curve following an intravenous dose.
Clearance of the drug due to renal excretion.
Clearance of the drug due to hepatic enzyme activity and biliary excretion.

This assay quantifies the expression level of the entire gene pool in a cell or a subpopulation (e.g. tissue-specific gene expression, kinases) using either microarray, bead method, RNASeq, or reporter gene method.
